{
  "answer": "**Death (marg).**\n\nThis famous couplet from Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib* (ghazal opening \"Aah ko chahiye ik umr asar hote tak\") declares that the sorrow of existence (*gham-e-hasti*, or \"ghum-e-hasti\") has no remedy except death.[^1][^2]\n\nThe original Urdu reads:  \nغَمْ ہَسْتِیْ کَا اسَدْ کِسْ سֵ ہُوْ جُزْ مَرْگْ عِلَاجْ  \nشَمْعْ ہَرْ رَنگْ مَیْںْ جَلْتِیْ ہَیْْ سَحَرْ ہَوْتَےْ تَکْ[^3]\n\nA common English rendering is:  \n\"What cure for life's great sorrow, Asad, say?  \nA candle burns in every way till morning's light.\"[^1]\n\nGhalib (pen name Asad) compares human life to a candle that flickers desperately in every color until dawn (death) arrives, underscoring life's transient pain with no other relief.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/translation/#p-82d15b).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/transliteration/#p-ab88c8). (Transliteration: \"Gham-e-hasti ka Asad kis se ho juz marg ilaaj / Shama har rang mein jalti hai seher hote tak.\")\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/original/#p-ab88c8).",
